e characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cooper","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a maker and repairer of wooden vessels such as barrels, tubs, buckets, casks, and vats, from Middle English <i>couper</i>, <i>cowper</i> (apparently from Middle Dutch <i>kūper</i>, a derivative of <i>kūp</i> ‘tub, container’, which was borrowed independently into English as <i>coop</i>). The prevalence of the surname, its cognates, and equivalents bears witness to the fact that this was one of the chief specialist trades in the Middle Ages throughout Europe. In North America, the English surname has absorbed some cases of like-sounding cognates from other languages, for example Dutch   Kuiper  .","Americanized form of Jewish (Ashkenazic) <b>Kupfer</b> and <b>Kupper</b> (see   Kuper  ).","Dutch: occupational name for a buyer or merchant, Middle Dutch <i>coper</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Kuiper","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Gerrit, Hendrik, Willem, Harm, Klaas, Kort, Marinus, Nicolaas, Wouter.","Dutch: occupational name for a cooper, Middle Dutch <i>cup(e)re</i>."]},{"name":"Couper","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Cooper  ."]},{"name":"Hooper","meanings":["English (southwestern): occupational name for a cooper, someone who fitted wooden or metal hoops on wooden casks and barrels, or a barrel-maker, from Middle English <i>hoper</i>, an agent derivative of <i>hop</i> ‘hoop, band’. Compare   Cooper  ."]},{"name":"Coop","meanings":["English (Lancashire): metonymic occupational name for a cooper, from Middle English <i>coupe</i>, <i>cupe</i> ‘tub, cask’ (from Latin <i>cūpa</i>), probably used for a cooper; compare   Cooper  . In some cases the surname may have been derived from a pub or house sign.","Americanized form of German or Dutch   Koop  .","History: It was David Koop (his father's surname also spelled <i>Kupe</i>) from Germany whose surname was changed to <i>Coop</i> after he settled in PA toward the end of the 18th century. He later moved to VA."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Simon De Cooper was born in 1375, in Bedford,